<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="b8efffdb-cdb5-5934-bb76-f4432ecb13a8" activityNameId="af4d7894-a22b-4e5d-b7d0-d2850818fa4f" parentActivityId="d1439cdb-76d0-48e2-917e-63f47bec43f3" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">acetaldehyde production, ethylene oxidation</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Acetaldehyde</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Aldehyde</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Ethanal</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Acetic aldehyde</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Ethyl aldehyde</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> 75-07-0</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with acetaldehyde being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of acetaldehyde by means of direct oxidation of ethylene (Wacker process), which is the most widely used method for producing acetaldehyde. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Acetaldehyde (C2H4O, CAS N° 75-07-0) is a colorless, and mobile, liquid with a pungent, suffocating odor that is slightly fruity when diluted. Moreover, it is completely miscible with water and most organic solvents.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Acetaldehyde is used in the manufacturing of pyrine and pyridine bases, peracetic acid, 1,3-butylene glycol, and others. Acetaldehyde could also oxidized with oxygen (or air) to yield acetic acid, and acetic anhydride or reduced to ethanol. Furthermore, acetaldehyde could activate the oxidation of p-xylene to terephthalic acid and of ethanol to acetic acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources. Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Eckert, M., Fleischmann, G., Jira, R., Bolt, H. M. and Golka, K. 2006. Acetaldehyde. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0 No. 8. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1986)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Ethylene is the most important starting material for the production of acetaldehyde and most of the present capacity works by its direct oxidation (Wacker process). One- and two-stage versions of the process are on stream. In the one-stage method, an ethylene-oxygen mixture reacts with the catalyst solution. In the two-stage process the reaction is carried out with ethylene and then with oxygen in two separate reactors. The catalyst solution is alternately reduced and oxidized. At the same time the degree of oxidation of the catalyst changes alternately. Air is used instead of pure oxygen for the catalyst oxidation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">C2H4 +  0.5O2 --&gt; C2H4O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">This dataset covers the direct oxidation (Wacker process) of the acetaldehyde production. Namely, ethylene and oxygen, along with a recycle stream, are fed to a reactor filled with the catalyst solution, under slight pressure. The reactor effluent is scrubbed with water, and the top gaseous mixture is the recycled into the reactor. Finally, the scrubbed mixture is fed into a distillation column.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The direct oxidation of ethylene is catalysed with an aqueous solution of PdCl2 and CuCl2. Notably, only a small amount of PdCl2 is used in this process since the metallic palladium is reoxidized by CuCl2 that, in turn, is regenerated with oxygen.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed, while the catalytic system is not covered.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Eckert, M., Fleischmann, G., Jira, R., Bolt, H. M. and Golka, K. 2006. Acetaldehyde. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Althaus H.-J., Chudacoff M., Hischier R., Jungbluth N., Osses M. and Primas A. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0 No. 8. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1989-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 1989) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
